Part I - Prosper Loan Data

by Grazyna Ostrowska

Introduction

Dataset includes information on 113,937 Prosper loan records, encompassing loan status and various attributes such as borrower rate (or interest rate), employment status, recommendation count, borrower income, and more.

Variable definitions can be found here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1gDyi_L4UvIrLTEC6Wri5nbaMmkGmLQBk-Yx3z0XDEtI/edit?gid=0#gid=0

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset has 113937 rows and 81 columns. Each row contain information about a single loan. Variable definitions can be found here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1gDyi_L4UvIrLTEC6Wri5nbaMmkGmLQBk-Yx3z0XDEtI/edit?gid=0#gid=0

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I would like to check which features should be investigated considering loan default.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I think that following features will help me investigate loan default: Term, LoanStatus, borrowerRate, ListingCategory (numeric), EmploymentStatusDuration, EmploymentStatus, CurrentCreditLines, DebtToIncomeRatio, StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginalAmount, InvestmentFromFriendsAmount and Investors.

# plot count plot

def get_countplot(dataframe, column, title):
    
    """display count plot for a column
    column - input variable, column name to plot
    dataframe - data frame to use
    title - graph title
    """
    ax= sns.countplot(dataframe, x=column, order = dataframe[column].value_counts().index, stat="percent")
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate('{:.1f}'.format(p.get_height()), (p.get_x()+0.25, p.get_height()+0.01))
        
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90);

Conclusions

I analised the dataset consisting of 113,937 Prosper loan records, encompassing loan status and various attributes such as borrower rate (or interest rate), employment status, recommendation count, borrower income, and more.

I wa interested which features should be investigated considering loan default.

I decided to analyse Term, LoanStatus, borrowerRate, ListingCategory (numeric), EmploymentStatusDuration, EmploymentStatus, CurrentCreditLines, DebtToIncomeRatio, StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginalAmount, InvestmentFromFriendsAmount and Investors features.

As I was interested in defaulted vs non-defaulted loans I transformed Loans Status values into Defaulted and NonDefaulted. Only 4.4% of loans were defaulted loans.

I changed format of ListingCategory from numeric to character. More than 50% of loans are debt consolidation loans. Almost 15% of loans are in 'Not Available' category.

I inputed Missing value for missing entries in EmploymentStatus column to check percent of missing values and display it in the graph. 87.6% of people that have a loans are employed (employed, full time or self employed). Employment status is not available for 4.7 loans.

For numeric features I did not change missing values as it could impact graphs and conclusions.

Most of loans were 36 months long and 75% of loans were at 2.5% interest rate or lower. Most loan owners (75%) worked for 137 months or no longer than 137 months. Loan owner had an average of 10 current credit lines. Average stated monthly income was 5607. Loan original amount ranges from 1000 to 35000. 75% dollar amount of investments that were made by friends is 0, but the maximum value of investments made by friends was 25000. Average number of investors that funded the loan was 80, maximum number of investors was 1189.

Most popular listing category for non defaulted loans is debt consolidation. For defaulted loans 'not available' category occurs most often. Among defaulted loans debt consolidation is the second most numerous category.

People that were employed or worked full-time most often borrowed loans that did not default. Most common emplyment statuses among defaulted loans were 'full-time' and 'not available'.

Usually people take out 36-month loans.

Numeric features that I analysed have weak correlation, below 0.4 absolute value. Borrower APR, lender yield and borrower rate are highly correlated as this features are interdependent and the calulation is similar.

Most defaulted loans are 36-month long and 60-month long. For 36-month loans there are defaulted loans with debt to income ratio equal 10 and debt to income ratio below 2. I observe the same in 60-month loans. 12-month defaulted loans have debt to income ratio below 2.

The most popular loans are with a small number of investors. I observed outliers regarding investments from friends amount in all loan terms.
